==English==

===Etymology===
1644, from {{bor|en|la|perennis||lasting through the whole year}} (itself from {{m|la|per-||through}} + {{m|la|annus||year}}) + {{af|en|-al}}; {{glossary|surface analysis}} {{confix|en|per|ennial}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/pəˈɹɛni.əl/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-perennial.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Lasting or remaining active throughout the [[year]], or all the time.
#: {{ux|en|a '''perennial''' stream}}
# {{lb|en|botany|of a plant}} Having a [[life cycle]] of more than two years.
#: {{cot|en|annual|biennial}}
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} Continuing without [[cessation]] or [[intermission]]; [[perpetual]]; never [[failing]].
#: {{syn|en|perpetual|permanent|unceasing}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1790|authorlink=Edmund Burke|first=Edmund|last=Burke|title=[[s:Reflections on the Revolution in France|Reflections on the Revolution in France]]|passage=The '''perennial''' existence of bodies corporate and their fortunes are things particularly suited to a man who has long views…}}
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} [[enduring|Enduring]]; [[lasting]]; [[timeless]].
#: {{syn|en|timeless|everlasting|perpetual|Thesaurus:eternal}}
#: {{ux|en|His artwork has a '''perennial''' beauty.}}
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} [[recurrent|Recurrent]]; appearing or recurring again and again.
#: {{syn|en|recurring|repetitious|Thesaurus:repetitive}}
#: {{ux|en|Change is a '''perennial''' theme in politics.}}
#: {{ux|en|a '''perennial''' candidate}}

